No, apparently not. The creature hissed only and tried to fly directly at Thassalin. Fortunately, Thassalin, despite his size, was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi let out a cry as she almost lost her grip on Thassalin's smooth scales.
„HOW CAN WE KILL THEM?“, screamed Nyssi.
„AIM FOR THEIR HEADS!“
„THAT WILL BE DIFFICULT!“
Thassalin hissed and then drew a circle, closer to the mountain he called home. The dark beast followed, but got slightly panicky when it was hit by a beam of fire from behind. It had not noticed that it was no longer alone. It became even more panicky when Thassalin slowed down and then flung his tail against her head, throwing her off course.
Rumbling and snarling, it flew upwards and spat into the air. Everything suddenly turned dark, as if the monster sucked the light from the sky into itself and replaced it with a cloud of eternal night.
As he suddenly could see nothing anymore, Thassalin tried to retreat. He felt himself scraping along the tree branches before finally crashing into a clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where he had fallen and shot directly at him, dragging the black cloud with it.
"Kayel!", shouted Tenuk as he slid out of the cloud and began circling to look for Nyssi and Thassalin in the darkness below. "What should we do now, Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
Below, Nyssi struggled to her feet. She was sure she had broken something, but her strange, supernatural healing powers had already started to take effect. Unfortunately, this did not apply to Thassalin. He leaned exhausted against the only tree that had not collapsed under his weight. Nyssi tried her best to get close to Thassalin, but she could barely see two meters. Everything was pitch black and shrouded in eerie shadows. And within this shadow, something was screaming and screeching.
A terrifying, armored tail crashed next to Nyssi onto the ground and knocked her down. However, she noticed that the tail was just wildly flailing and not deliberately trying to hit her. The beast, or rather the little that Nyssi could see and hear of it, growled and slashed at the shadows it had created with its claws. Something shot through the darkness, stabbed the monster, and confused it.
Suddenly, a gunshot cracked through the fog, and the monster fell silent, collapsed to the ground, and lay motionless. The darkness around them dissipated, and they saw what had happened: Kayel stood on the beast, heavily panting while holding his rifle.
"That was probably... The craziest shadow leap I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon...", Kabel gasped for air. His eyes glowed almost black, and a dark energy surrounded his body. But while he was still speaking, color returned to his armor, and his eyes regained their normal yellow color.
It took a moment for Nyssi to understand what had happened. They had all known that Kayel possessed these strange shadow powers. He rarely used them, because most found them eerie and quite intimidating. But Nyssi had not known that Kayel could also use these powers in any kind of darkness. And the way Kayel was behaving, he obviously seemed quite surprised as well.
"Are you okay?," burst out of Nyssi.
"Yes, I'm fine. I killed something, I'll be back to normal soon." Kayel looked at his work while Tenuk flew down, landed next to him, and took on his normal spastic form again.
Now that the beast was no longer moving, they could see better what it was. Its skin was raven black and slimy, but the slime remained firmly attached to its body. It had four wings and four extremities, all ending in long, thin claws, and two straight horns extended from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what the hell they were looking at, something screeched and jumped out of a nearby bush. However, it did not reach them, because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side and caused the monster to skid to a stop in front of Nyssis feet. Nyssi wanted to take no chances. She grabbed her shotgun, fired without thinking at its skull, and the creature died on the spot.
„Ups…“, murmured Retvik from the driver's seat before awkwardly turning off the engine and getting out of the truck. „Uh, that wasn't actually intentional. Are you all okay?“
„You missed the whole action，“ scolded Tenuk. „Where were you?“
„You just left me standing there. I came as quickly as I could…“, sighed Retvik. „May I ask what those terrible creatures are?“
Retvik's question was fortunately answered by Thassalin, who had managed to pull himself together again. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a bit dazed, but not seriously injured.
"YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTIIDS! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. CREATURES THAT WERE GONE FROM HERE WHEN THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"You mean the terrible god-monster creature that we... helped to kill?" stammered Tenuk.
"YES. EXACTLY THAT. THERE MAY BE MORE. BUT I COULD NOT SHOOT IN THE HEAD. I HAVE NO FIREARM. AND TWO AGAINST ONE IS UNFAIR, OR?" Thassalin hobbled to Kayel and patted his head. "THANK YOU VERY MUCH, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. JUST NOT SO MURDEROUS AND NOT SO CAPABLE OF KILLING WHOLE UNIVERSES."
"Uh... thanks... I guess..." Kayel shrugged. "So, are we done here?"
Nyssi shrugged. She grabbed her camera and took some pictures of the now definitely dead creatures. Then she drew her favorite weapon, the decorated god of death dagger, and began to cut off one of the creature's horns. Then she moved on to the second one. But as Nyssi was just finishing, the creatures suddenly burst into flames and turned into a pile of ash within seconds. The same happened to the horns that Nyssi had cut off.
"Well, that's simultaneously practical and impractical...," Nyssi sighed. "But at least I have the photos, hopefully."
